  <!-- Standfirst paragraph — styled as 22px opener, gets drop cap -->
  <p>Government and defence cleaning is not a commodity service. It operates inside one of the most compliance-intensive procurement environments in Australia. where documentation, workforce integrity, security screening and audit evidence are baseline requirements, not differentiators.</p>

  <h2>What Government Cleaning Involves</h2>
  <p>
    Cleaning programs for federal, state and territory government facilities require documented procedures, verifiable outcomes and the ability to operate within security classifications. At minimum, this includes routine cleaning against a documented specification, waste and hygiene management, compliance with workplace health and safety obligations, and evidencing of work completed for audit purposes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Government contracts typically include key performance indicators, service level agreements and formal reporting requirements that go substantially beyond what is expected in private sector cleaning.
  </p>

  <CalloutBox heading="What this means for procurement teams">
    <p>When evaluating cleaning providers for government facilities, look beyond price and insurance certificates. Ask specifically for documented quality management procedures, evidence of previous government contract performance, and confirmation of workforce background-checking processes. These are the indicators that separate compliant providers from those who will struggle under contract audit.</p>
  </CalloutBox>

  <h2>Where It Applies</h2>
  <p>Government cleaning covers a broad and diverse range of facility types across federal, state and territory jurisdictions:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Courthouses and law enforcement facilities</li>
    <li>Defence sites and military installations</li>
    <li>Transport infrastructure including bus stations, rail stations and depots</li>
    <li>Public service office complexes and ministerial buildings</li>
    <li>Department facilities including Centrelink, Medicare, ATO and equivalent state agencies</li>
    <li>Correctional facilities and detention centres</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Each facility type carries specific compliance, security and operational requirements that must be built into the cleaning program. not managed as exceptions.
  </p>

