  <h2>Risks and Compliance Requirements</h2>
  <p>
    Operating a cleaning program in a government or defence environment without adequate compliance infrastructure creates significant and measurable risk. Common gaps that surface during contract audits include:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Missing or inadequate method statements and risk assessments</li>
    <li>Failure to meet security clearance and background-check requirements</li>
    <li>Non-compliant industrial relations arrangements, particularly around award coverage</li>
    <li>Lack of documented incident response procedures</li>
    <li>Inadequate supervision ratios or quality assurance processes</li>
    <li>Absence of corrective action records when deficiencies are identified</li>
  </ul>

  <QuoteBlock
    quote="Government facilities require a provider who can evidence compliance. not just claim it. The difference is apparent at the first contract audit."
    attribution="CPC Compliance Team"
  />

  <h2>Standards and Expectations in Australia</h2>
  <p>Government and defence cleaning in Australia is governed by a range of overlapping standards and frameworks. Providers operating in this sector are expected to demonstrate:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>ISO 9001 Quality Management. documented procedures, internal auditing, corrective action</li>
    <li>ISO 14001 Environmental Management. waste handling, chemical management, environmental monitoring</li>
    <li>ISO 45001 Occupational Health and Safety. site risk assessment, incident management, WHS compliance</li>
    <li>Modern Slavery Act 2018 (Cth). annual reporting and supply chain transparency</li>
    <li>Commonwealth Procurement Rules and equivalent state frameworks</li>
    <li>Department of Defence security classification requirements where applicable</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    Meeting these standards requires documented management systems, trained staff, and the organisational infrastructure to maintain and evidence compliance on an ongoing basis. not just at contract commencement.
  </p>

