  <h2>How CPC Delivers Government and Defence Cleaning</h2>
  <p>
    CPC has delivered government and defence cleaning services since 1995. Our approach is built around documented procedures, trained staff, and the quality management infrastructure required to perform and evidence compliant work. Each site operates under:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>A documented cleaning specification linked to the contract schedule</li>
    <li>A site-specific risk assessment and method statement</li>
    <li>A trained and background-screened workforce, with security clearances where required</li>
    <li>Regular internal auditing against the KPIs specified in the contract</li>
    <li>A formal reporting framework that provides clients with verifiable evidence of service delivery</li>
  </ul>

  <h2>Workforce and Training Model</h2>
  <p>
    CPC operates a vetted workforce model combining directly employed core staff with contractor partners who meet our compliance, training and screening requirements. Every person working on a CPC contract. direct or contractor. operates under the same documented procedures, training programs and audit framework.
  </p>
  <p>
    Government and defence environments often require police checks, working with children checks, and in some cases AGSVA security clearances. Our workforce management infrastructure supports these requirements at scale, including the maintenance of screening records and compliance documentation for audit purposes.
  </p>

  <h2>Reporting, Auditing and Evidence of Work</h2>
  <p>
    Government clients require more than verbal assurance of service delivery. CPC provides a structured reporting framework as a standard component of every government contract:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li>Regular service reports against specified KPIs, delivered to contract schedule</li>
    <li>Audit results from internal quality audits, with documented findings and corrective actions</li>
    <li>Third-party audit access where required under contract terms</li>
    <li>Client-facing dashboards for larger contracts, providing real-time visibility of service status</li>
  </ul>
  <p>
    This reporting structure is built into our service model. not added as a reactive response to client requests.
  </p>

  <h2>Social Procurement and Indigenous Engagement</h2>
  <p>
    Many government contracts include Indigenous procurement targets, social enterprise obligations or broader social value requirements. CPC has an established social procurement framework, Indigenous employment pathways, and documented supplier diversity practices that support government clients in meeting their social procurement obligations. including requirements under Commonwealth Indigenous Procurement Policy and equivalent state frameworks.
  </p>

